em before they were deported. He lived with indigenous families in the mountains of Oaxaca and in farm labor camps in the U.S., planted and harvested corn, picked strawberries, and accompanied sick workers to clinics and hospitals. This “embodied anthropology” deepens our theoretical understanding of the ways in which social inequalities and suffering come to be perceived as normal and natural in society and in health care. All of the book award money and royalties from the sales of this book have been donated to farm worker unions, farm worker organizations and farm worker projects in consultation with farm workers who appear in the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropologist.  aanthropology.  aarizona desert.  abiography.  aborderlands.  acrossing the border.  acultural analysis.  adeportation.  adeported immigrants.  aembodied anthropology.  afarm labor camps.  ahealth and wellness.  ahealth care.  ahuman rights.  aimmigration stories.  aimmigration.  amemoir.  amexican immigrants.  aoaxaca.  asocial inequalities.  aus mexico relations.1 aBourgois, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027513340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095479340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954793423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954793/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY